segments.text: Can you tell me any specific tactics that were used to improve the mortality rate of the wounded?
Because we had so few casualties, and certainly that's due to the quick helicopter rescue.
I don't know if I understand the question.
Tactics were used to improve the mortality rate?
You mean that somebody got hurt and they didn't die, they were successfully operated on?
Right.
Oh, okay.
Yeah, based on your World War II or Korean War, your hospitals were pretty far to the rear and they were brought back by vehicle or any way they could.
During the war in Vietnam, helicopters were brought in.
Mostly you had a landing area when you brought your people in to fight, or that landing area was cleared with trees and structures.
to bring people out.
And you did have people who got out much quicker than World War II, got back to the hospital, and were saved more than what you had in World War II because of the helicopter.
And you had a lot of sharp people working in Vietnam, riding on the helicopters.
Your aid men were doing things

keep people alive on the way flying back, but not only of the helicopters transporting to hospitals, but you had fixed hospitals, I mean built up hospitals in Saigon, you had the ARAVAC from Saigon to Guam or to Hawaii, Tripoli Army Hospital in Hawaii, to the hospital in San Francisco, Brooks Army Hospital here in Texas, so you had
Jet aircraft bringing them wounded back, so a big improvement than what you had during World War II.
In 1969, 540,000 men were in Vietnam, but only 80,000 were actually involved in combat.
Why is that?
Well, I'll take your statistic, because I don't know the ratio of which ones were which.
I can only surmise that you had a lot of support people and you had a lot of different jobs going on.
Like I said before, we had people who did work back on staff areas to supply aircraft, to build airfields, to be advisors to different types of staff people.
I mean, not only did we have advisors to fighting combat units, we had advisors to Army staffs, Navy staffs, and what have you in the Vietnamese high command.
And I did know that we had more people not fighting than were in fact fighting.
I don't know what the ratio was, but
A lot of it was just trying to maintain what we had.
We had a lot of security people involved.

Whenever you put up, again, going back to the tactics we had, whenever you put an installation up, and we can use Tonsenick Air Force Base or any Air Force Base or any kind of supply storage area, you had to have somebody guard that or that place would be gone.
You brought in scout dogs or you brought in guard dogs and
you and if it's something sensitive you put American security people on it.

You might have Vietnamese with you but if it's something that you really want to protect again not knowing who the players are in some cases you put American people on for security so there's a lot of American people on doing security work.
Do you ever feel that there was
different than other wars an increased number of supply for comforts, like one hot meal a day perhaps, or some things that were made to make the Americans feel more comfortable in daily living.
Do you think that was ever excessive?
I can't say what it was in World War II since I wasn't in it, but I read some books on it.
think it was the type of war we were fighting in the jungle warfare that we, in fact, tried to make our soldiers as comfortable as possible when they came back in from fighting.
Because I was in the supply business with 101st, we ran out to them like a mini PX, PX meaning a little department store where you get
razor blades and candy and cigarettes and whatever.
We'd put it in the back of a truck or on a Connex container and fly it.
A Connex container is a big steel box.
We'd fly it out to what we call a fire base where they'd come back in and rest and provide.
We also provided different types of special service shows.
Not like the Bob Hope show, which they came a little bit smaller shows for them when they got back in.
We provided...

picture shows for them on these fire bases, and of course all this you didn't have during World War II, or I don't know about it, but you did probably provide them quite a few things that you probably didn't do in World War II, but again it was a type of war I felt, and also you had a lot of people looking at you all the time, public opinion, and Johnny writing home to

his parents who complained to the congressman or whatever, I think had a lot of bearing on a lot of treatment that they've got to bring down the idea that all we did was just push him out there, have him fight for a year, and if they made it fine, they came home.
There was a lot of people who couldn't take this type of life, and you read about it all the time, about people saying they still...
Some of them play on the idea, but still having psychiatric problems and what have you.
But when the soldiers came in for relax and R&R, they did do a lot for them.
We had donut girls, such as the Red Cross, would go out there and put on different types of shows for them if they could or provide them.
And some of this goes on here in the United States also.
And you and I have the same thing.
Off of our job, we're watching television or going out and doing something to relax our mind.
And we try to do the same thing out there when they were not actually in combat to provide them with some kind of service that they could forget about fighting.
Do you feel this might have been from American political pressure, that Americans were interested in making this a short, convenient war?
Well, I think everybody wanted it to be a short war, but it never got that way.
I don't know if I really understand your question.
providing them these services?
They felt that there would be a short war?
No.
This probably is a bad question.
But I just felt that Vietnam was different from my readings than the other wars.
And I guess it would be since it was so hot and in jungle.
But it seemed like we were spending a lot of time on supply when there were men there that didn't really have to be there.
And I just was wondering if that was political pressure from mothers that, you know, we weren't attacked in this war.
We
we went over there to help him out.
I wonder if because of that, it wasn't a national crisis.
It was something that... Well, I think most of the people back in 62, 63, even when Kennedy was in office, what have you, felt that we did have a national crisis in this.
The domino effect that if we lost Vietnam, so would we lose Cambodia and
Thailand, and on and on.
I think we're still having some problems.
We've lost Vietnam.
We've lost Cambodia, that's for sure.
Thailand's got all kinds of problems.
I think that you will see as time goes by, and we're having the same problem with other countries in South America, that if we don't do something, the economy's going to take over.
And we can't end up an island to ourselves.
And I think we really thought this would probably be a short war.
I feel that we felt that we could just send over advisors.
And after a couple of years of advising, the South Vietnamese would take over the fighting.
And we would pull our advisors out.
And they would win the war.
That didn't happen that way.
Is there anything specifically that you can name
as a point in time where the American people turned from approval of the war to disapproval?
Oh, I don't know if I could really say at any time that they turned from approval to disapproval.
I think the American people didn't want to get involved in it to start with.
And when we start having a lot of casualties,
And when they saw it on television every night, then the people said, hey, let's get out of here.
Why should we fight for Vietnam?
We had the same type of casualties during World War II, but it wasn't on television as much.
I think the biggest problem, from my point of view, was that the American people never knew where
where the line was.
In World War II, when we took this country, or that country, or this city, or that city, you could stick your pins in your map and say, hi, we're progressing.

In this war, the only way you could figure out if you're progressing or not, and it was unknown if that was even correct, was how many things you killed, or how many people got hurt, or how much equipment.
And American people just didn't realize that,
One night you might have a piece of the ground, and the next night you don't have it.
So it's hard to stick a pin in the map and look at progress.
You can look at a statistical map and see how things go up and down.
But American people wanted to look, you're winning this ground.
I think they compared the Vietnam War with World War II, and there was no comparison to do.
Did you see a change in the civilian behavior of the Vietnamese from the time elapsed between your tours?
Okay, you're talking about Vietnamese or you're talking about Americans?
Vietnamese.

No, I think, see I had left before the fall of Vietnam and the two years I spent there, I got the impression that the South Vietnamese, the ones I had worked with during the year I was there, were really trying to get out and do something
and save their country.

I'm sure most of the officers that I worked with are dead now because sitting with them and I went home with them, ate in their home and played with their kids and all that, that they were really against the communist way of life.
And I would say that they didn't stop and they probably fought to the end.
Sure, you read about stories where certain divisions

the south viennese fled from way and came back and people started running to the rear and what have you i'm sure that went on but the unit i was with i doubt very seriously if some of the officers that that i knew did anything but die
One interesting question is, did you see evidence of inter-service rivalry between the Army and the Air Force, especially in the responsibility of the helicopters?
No.
Again, I've got to go back to when I was advisor.
We took help from anybody.
When you're an advisor on the ground and you have no helicopters of your own, and that's where we were.
We were a security unit.
We had no helicopters asked for from the Vietnamese side of the house.
A few helicopters, yes, to pick up the wounded.
We had no artillery support from the Vietnamese side.
We did have support from helicopters from the 1st Division.
And we had artillery support from the 1st Division because I worked out a deal where the 1st Division was hunting for a place to put an artillery battery.
And so we gave them some land right in the middle of our area.

So with the understanding, which is very obvious, and when I talked to the commander, the VD's commander, he thought it was a great idea, that if you've got an American artillery battalion sitting right in the middle of your area, if they get attacked, they're going to start shooting back.
If we get attacked, they're going to start shooting back also because we're going to be protecting them.
We provide security for them also.
So that worked both ways.
Uh, we provided infantry security for them and whenever we needed help, they fired a few rounds for us.
And, uh, it's hard to really say, uh, why certain things go on over there.
Uh, when you look at, in my, in my area, you look, I had one little small area.
I was not on the, um, army command or anything else in Saigon.
where I could see a big picture.
I was only looking at a small area, I'd say.
What was the most frustrating aspect of your service in Vietnam?
Which time?
The first time or the second time?
I guess the first time, we'll break it down in two parts.
The first time was trying to get people to do things.
Some of the South Vietnamese soldiers and some of the officers really felt that unless they came up with this idea, then it wasn't a good idea.
And it was very difficult for a lot of Americans to try to get their ideas over.
And I would suppose that some ideas got over,
You had to be very careful with telling them to do something without offending them.
They were very cognizant of the fact that it was their country.
And you never said anything to a senior officer, a battalion commander, which I advise as a senior officer, in front of his soldiers.
You had to always talk to him.

away from his people, because if you would say anything, why don't you do this, or go do that, in front of his staff, or in front of his office, it'll never get done, because for him, it's losing face, and they were very worried about losing face, but if he thought it was his idea, you sat in a corner or something and talked with him, or you had lunch with him,
if you could stand some of the food they ate.
And I felt that if you could sit down with the officer and talk to him and let him think it's his idea or suggest things and kind of hope he runs with it, then you'd probably be all right.
But the worst thing that any of the officers could ever do was tell a Vietnamese commander in front of his people or in front of his staff
You should do this.
You can forget it.
It won't get done.
The second time over there, I think, with the 101st Airborne, the hardest thing I feel was a frustrating thing was that during the day, you would be fighting in an area or resupplying an area.
And it would be a nice and friendly area.
And at night, it could be the worst area over there.
You really didn't know who the players were all the time.
And I feel, personally, I feel that was a big problem with all the units over there.
All the Viennese look alike, and they could change any time they want.
They could be on your side during the day, and they'd get you at night.
You never knew who these people were.
Everybody wore black pajamas.
That was a great thing.
Everybody wore black pajamas.
And you see this guy walking down the road,
You didn't know whether you wanted to shoot him or not, or at least pull out your arms.
But if you had a red communist AK type of a rifle, you were almost sure that that guy was against you.
Most of the South Vietnamese soldiers and the, like, reserve units they had would not carry any VC weapons, because Americans were known to shoot first and ask questions afterwards sometimes.
or their own people, American helicopters might see them and say, hey, that's a NVA outfit down there.
And somebody might call a jury for them or whatever.
So they very seldom ever carried any weapon other than the Americans.
But I think that's the two of the frustrating things, is trying to be a diplomat with your counterpart and trying to tell who the players are when you're running around.
Now I'd like to focus perhaps on some of the civilians of war.
Can you tell me in what ways did the peasants of the jungle vary from the people living in Saigon and more protected communities?
Yeah, okay.
Going back to 1068 again, the year I was over there as advisor, we were out in the field quite a bit.
And most of the farmers that
or out in the farmland, who are not in the city or built up areas, all they wanted to do, they didn't give a damn, to be truthful, of who was in power.
All they wanted to do was form their land and be left alone by both sides.
And that's some of the reasons why during the day, again, they were friendly to the Americans or the South Vietnamese.
And when the South Vietnamese and Americans left,
The VC came in at night, which was a kind of a normal operation.
They were friendly to them.
They didn't care who was running the show.
Just leave me alone.
Let me do my rice paddy or grow my whatever they were growing, for the most part it was rice.
And they didn't care who was in power.
And when you get back in the built up areas, back in these towns and Saigon, for example, yeah, they did.
have a feeling for who was going to be in power, and they were more into the politics end of things.
But the former out in the field, as long as his rice paddy grew, he didn't care who would run the show.
How were the women, the Vietnamese women, treated?
What was their status in the Vietnamese culture?
Well, nothing like there are in the United States, that's for sure.
Vietnamese women, for the most part, treated by other Vietnamese, I guess you mean, they were something to be tolerated, you might say.
There was very few women who were in any political positions.
The women were to bear children, and to keep the house clean, work in the rice paddies,
The role was much less to do what they're told.
And they even were supposedly to walk behind the man.
I think it's, I forgot what it is now, but it was two or three steps behind and two or three steps to the left or right.
I can't remember what it was now.
But they had really no rules at all.
If a male child, if a parent had children,
family had children, and the first one was a girl and the second was a boy, the boy child would have more authority in the family than the first born girl child.
So the women didn't have much of a role in anything.
How did you deal with the cultural differences in Eastern and Western moms?
Well, I don't think I really did.
I worked with
my counterpart, and I was fortunate that, again, he spoke English.
He had been trained in the United States.
He had gone to a basic officer's course at Fort Benning.
He was a Catholic, and I'm Catholic.
So I accompanied him to his church services, which is the same as mine.
Some things they did different than what I would see done here in the United States.
But anyway, he was Catholic.
I was Catholic.
And so we got along all right in the religion aspects.
And he took me to his home.
And we advisors didn't have very much of a home.
We had something provided by the government.
But it was pretty nice.
But we were either with some other group of American officers, or we were with the battalion.
And with the battalion, you were probably in tents.
But when you're with other advisors in an advisor compound, then we were an old French hotel of some sort when I was advising.
But again, they did their thing.
And you tried to learn.
I tried to learn what they were doing because it was interesting.
I didn't have any cultural problems.
per se, because I tried to go along with the things that they showed me.
I remember one occasion, and this is kind of funny, somewhat.
Again, remember that I didn't understand all the Vietnamese I should have understood.
We went to a party, which was a number of senior officers of the battalion, and I went to it, sitting next to the battalion commander,
He toasted everybody, and he had a glass of something, and I had it in front of me, and everybody toasted it, and we drank it, and it was horrible.
Yeah, it was horrible.
It looked like tomato juice.
And I said to him, I said, what did we just drink?
And he says, whiskey, very good whiskey.
And I said, I know, but what's the red stuff?
I said, that don't taste like tomato juice to me.
He says, oh, no, that's goat's blood.
It was whiskey and goat's blood.
Very good.
He says, very good.
I guess you know what we had for supper that night?
The goat.
And he didn't like hamburgers, I found out, as we went down the road.
And so I never had to have any more goat's blood, because every time that he would say anything about goat's blood, I would say, well, you didn't eat my hamburger, so we had a standoff.
So I never had any more goat's blood.
Do you think America's effort with the war was obstructed by any barriers between their way of thinking and ours, besides what you mentioned?
Oh, I'm sure there was in some cases.
Again, here, you're talking about the overall war that I wasn't involved in.
I was involved in a very small segment, but from what I read, I would say that the
The American way of life and the Oriental or Viennese way of life is not the same.
They have different values and hold different things that they believe in.
And I'm sure that there was problems between the Oriental and the American way of thinking.
You can just look at the truth conferences that Kissinger ran back and forth on and everybody else.
thinking that they had an agreement.
No, they didn't have an agreement.
Yes, they did have an agreement.
The oriental outlook, I feel, is they'll wait till hell freezes over to get their own way.
They will talk to you and agree with you and agree with you and talk to you and smile and everything else.
But they're not going to do it.
They don't want to do it.
It's not going to be done.
And I think that's the same thing that
Nixon and Kissinger and all of them had.
A lot of people agreed with what they wanted to do, but they only stalled food around until they got what they wanted, getting us out of the country and then taking over.
The media played a big role in the Vietnam War.
What do you think of the media coverage of Vietnam?
Well, I got involved with one
The man who came over to Vietnam was Charles Collingwood.
I have some pictures of him.
And that was the only time, and that was right after Tet, that I'd ever gotten any type of involvement with firsthand knowledge.
And I felt Charles Collingwood did a real fine job.
He came over there, and he was with the training center.
He wasn't with the unit I was with, but since the training center
had another officer that was involved, American officer that came down.
So I was working out with him and trying to help him set up all this stuff.
But anyway, Collingwood came over and he talked about the training and talked about the problems they had.
We knew that we had VCs that we were training because the way they would draft people, as I told you before, go down the street and grab them, we knew that people
that we were training was on the other side.
For that matter, we were very cautious, the sergeant and myself, that we tried to work together and stay together a lot so that we wouldn't get shot from behind.
We knew that there were VCs in the unit.
For that matter, at night, the trainees would not be given a weapon at night.
They would have a weapon during the day, and we'd give them ammunition during the day when they went to training ranges.
But at night,
the weapons were all taken away from them.
And of course we do the, you know, that's not, that seems kind of unusual during wartime, but we do basically the same thing in the American Army right now.

We train during the day, men have weapons during the day, and at night we lock them up in racks down the center of the floor of the barracks, or we put them in an arms room, only because we don't want them to accidentally shoot themselves.
But over there, the reason behind it was that you might end up with a couple of,
VCs running around trying to shoot people.
I'm not sure if you're aware of what happened.
At one point, the media covered a story where right in front of American eyes, a Buddhist doused himself with gasoline and put himself to suicide.
How do you think the Buddhist religion affected the decisions of the country?
Well, I thought there was a very influential group.
I also saw a film of when the general, the Viennese general shot and killed a VC in the street, and there was films of people doused themselves with gas.
I think even a few Americans in the United States here did something like that too.
But the Buddhists were
a very influential group.
They were just like another political party like the Democrats and Republicans we got.
They felt that they could do it better and it was a basketball back and forth between both of them.
A lot of your soldiers were Buddhist and believed in that way.
The priest, when they came in to
conduct services in our units when I was an advisor, were carded all kinds of rights and what have you.
Freedom of speech, you might say, or religion.
And I don't know what they were saying, but I know that they came in and conducted church service or whatever.
And they were a very potent group.
The Orientals believe in a lot of that,
and have different types of services and holidays and what have you.
So they were a very potent group.
Do you feel the average civilian of Vietnam was aware of the ideals of democracy and their countries being a testing ground for democracy?
Do you think they were aware of that?
Well, it depends on what kind of democracy you're talking about.
I don't think that any of them were aware of what we call democracy.
I think what they were looking at, and again, we've got to get back to the people in the built-up areas, because again here, the farmers didn't care about anything but their farmland.
I felt those who were trying to build a government, yeah, they had democracy, but their type of democracy
you could do what you wanted to do as long as you didn't do it against the government.
Some of the people in high places over there, I remember seeing General Two and a few of the other, General Key and his wife over there.
A lot of people felt that they were trying to set themselves up as king and queen

what have you and there was groups against them i think when you start talking about democracy the viennese had a different feeling of democracy than what you and i know it their democracy was stop the fighting and get on with life over there and that the government would have
I won't say dictatorial powers, but they had a big say in what the people were going to do, but it would be a democratic dictatorial shift, you might say.
One thing that I've learned in studying Vietnam is that a lot of times there were just things that were lost, you know, equipment, but also that there were people actively working
you know, both Vietnamese and Americans, that there was a black market set up for corruption.
Can you tell me examples?
It depends on what you're trying to say now.
Are you talking about a black market of luxury items or a black market of supplies for the war?
Well, both.
Yeah, there was quite a bit of luxury black market items.
The Americans were bringing in for their soldiers a lot of,

post-exchange items, and I don't know if you've heard of the post-exchange, it looks like a Walmart, okay, doing away with the furniture stuff and whatever, you know, stereos like this one here, and different types of pocket radios, and a lot of comfort items, and somehow, some of this stuff would get ripped off before it ever got to the post-exchange, or the beer got stolen, or the whiskey that
they had for the different clubs where it gets stolen.
Lo and behold, it come up on the streets.
There's a street called Tuto Street in Vietnam where all this stuff would appear just right on the streets.
And nobody seemed to do anything about it.
I mean, you could walk, if you couldn't find the PX, you walked down there and you might find it.
You might pay more for it.
But yeah, it was an open black market going on in Vietnam.
of that type of goods.
Of military goods, I didn't know of any military goods that were sold or bought by anybody.
I'm sure there might have been, but there were some accounting problems over there I know of.
I've heard of one story, whether it's true or not or not, that the Air Force was trying to order all kinds of parts for aircraft, millions of dollars of parts.
And they didn't even know it, but they had them already in their warehouse.
And they had a problem in just trying to figure out what's in these boxes.
And we had an accountability problem.

And they went back, and from where I hear it, they had a team that came over to Vietnam and had to sort through all these warehouses they had for aircraft parts to get everything in line, get them computerized, and whatever, so they could figure out what they had.
But the pleasure items, yeah, I saw a black marker on that.
But the military equipment, I didn't see anybody doing anything with that stuff.
In your opinion, why did the U.S. lose the war in Vietnam?
The bombing escalation?
Yeah, I think that, and like you just said, I think we lost the war in Vietnam.
I think we just didn't have the will to fight anymore.
The Army had the will to fight.
I think the American Army, or armed forces, not just the Army, had the will to fight.
But our politicians back here in the United States and our civilian people back in the United States just didn't have the will to fight anymore.
We, again, we were not carrying the war to the north.
We were just staying on our side.
We had, our politicians had made a lot of promises about getting the troops out by such and such a day, or this was gonna, we were gonna get out, win with honor, I think one of the cliches were.
And I think the North Vietnamese just said, well, if we keep stalling and keep stalling and keep stalling,
between the media and the politicians and the civilian side of the house, we can get them out of Vietnam, we can take over, and that's exactly what happened.
As soon as the Americans got out, and I forget now how many months, if it was months, everything after the Americans got their last units out, everything just fell apart.
We also had a problem on funding, too.
At that time, Congress and whatever was cutting back on funding for arms for South Vietnam.
And I really feel that the will to carry the war on to the north on the political end of it and the American civilian end of it was, hey,
It's their war.
Let the South Vietnamese fight their war.
Bring our boys home.
And if they can't hack it in South Vietnam, to hell with them.
And it went about that way.
We got our people out, and the whole thing fell apart.
In a general way, what did you perceive as your purpose in Vietnam?
What motivated you to be there?
Well, I really didn't have that much choice.

When I raised my right hand at Texas A&M and said I support the Constitution and do what I was told to do by the President, the Commander-in-Chief, I had a choice of one, quit in the Army or continue on what I wanted to do.
I chose to stay in the Army, and I stayed in there a little over 20 years.
So I went where I was told.
I went to Korea twice.
I went to Vietnam twice.
I went to Europe twice.
I had some good tours in France and what have you.
But I went over there based on I was told to go.

And I felt that my job over there was to try to, first time I went over, was try to assist the unit I was assigned to have them succeed in their role, the mission to secure the Air Force base and to secure the
training center and I felt my role was to assist that commander in doing that.
And I went to an extra 30 days of school to learn how to try to do that.
The second time I went over was again to support the American unit I was assigned to.
And it's just like you going to school.
If you don't want to go to school, you can quit.
say, I don't want to do it anymore.

An Army officer, United States Army, after he finishes his required time, whether it's six months, two years, or six years, or whatever else, how he got his commission, if he doesn't want to do that anymore, then he quits.
But I wanted to do it.
I wanted to continue my career, and I decided to do it.
And I did as best as I could based on what I was told to do.
Did you voluntarily return to Vietnam, or was that where you were sent?
No, I knew that I was ended up at least two or three times.
Some officers were more than that.
I voluntarily returned when I received a set of orders telling me to go back.
Right.
Do you see Vietnam in historical overview as a victory in any way for Americans?
What do you think we learned?
No, I don't think so.
I think that most Americans, and if you're talking to officers, and I would, I can't speak for general officers, but for the most part the officers I know, we really felt that we lost the war.
I think that we'll probably learn, but some of the things we're doing right now today probably doesn't show we learned too much of it, is that
if you're going to go out and win something or you're going to try to win something, you can't do a halfway job.
You've got to get out there and do it all the way.
You've got to use all your forces to do it.

If you're going to get involved in a warfare where you're going to have American soldiers on the ground using all their combat force, you've got to commit your combat force not only on the ground but your air also.
And I feel that
If anything, we learn out of this thing is that if we ever get involved in a jungle-type warfare again, we cannot sit back and fight in one little area.
You've got to go to the source of where all the problems are coming and give them a taste of the war.
Colonel Wilcox, I'm through with my questions, but would you like to add anything that you feel important?
